      "question_id": "101",
      "answer": "A stack is LIFO; you push and pop from the top, useful for function call stacks and DFS. A queue is FIFO; you enqueue at tail and dequeue at head, used for BFS and job scheduling. Implementation details: stacks can be implemented with arrays or linked lists; in an array-backed stack you maintain a top index, while queue implementations may use circular buffers to avoid shifting. Complexity: both have O(1) push/pop or enqueue/dequeue amortized. Example: using a stack for expression evaluation and a queue for breadth-first search on graph.",
